                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1057">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.62114 Mail/146: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Switzerland</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Harrison</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Bern</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-06-19">June 19,
                            1944</date>.<lb/>[Received June 20—3:34 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>3928. American Interests—Far East. POW and internee mail, Department’s 1851, May
                        29.<note n="68" xml:id="d1057fn68">Not printed.</note> Foreign Office note
                    June 17 states Swiss Legation, Tokyo, replies to contents Department 1379, April
                        21<note n="69" xml:id="d1057fn69">See footnote 47, <ref target="#pg_1030">p.
                            1030</ref>.</note> that Japanese authorities accept in principle
                    Department’s proposal. However, Ministry of Communications feels mail from Japan
                    should be sent to Moscow for retransmission Tehran by Soviet authorities.
                    Director Japanese post wrote in foregoing sense May 27 to Commissaire [of]
                    Postal Communications, Moscow.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Harrison</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
